description: From Middle English cote, from the Old English cote, the feminine form of cot (“small house”); doublet of cot (in the sense of “cottage”) and more distantly related to cottage. Cognate to Dutch kot.

entries.meaning: A small structure built to contain domesticated animals such as sheep, pigs or pigeons.

verbs.description: cote (third-person singular simple present cotes, present participle coting, simple past and past participle coted)

description: Probably related to French côté (“side”) via Middle French costé.

verbs.description: cote (third-person singular simple present cotes, present participle coting, simple past and past participle coted)

entries.meaning: To go side by side with; hence, to pass by; to outrun and get before.
